Be careful with plastic tea bags!
According to the Central News Agency, a recent Canadian study found that a package of plastic tea bags may release billions or even tens of billions of plastic particles, significantly higher than a person's estimated annual intake of microplastics, but so far there is no evidence that the intake of plastic particles will pose a threat to humans.
Researchers at the University of Margill in Canada found that dipping plastic tea bags into a cup of almost boiling hot water (95 degrees Celsius), tea bags will release about 11.6 billion plastic particles and 3.1 billion smaller nanoplastic particles into cups.
This amount is significantly higher than the amount of microplastics a person estimates to be ingested throughout the year.
According to research published earlier in 2019, the average person eats at least 50,000 microplastics a year and inhales the same amount of microplastics.
It is reported that the study was published in the "Journal of Environmental Science and Technology", and the researchers tested four different types of plastic commercial tea bags in Montreal stores and cafes, opened tea bags, and immersed the tea bags in almost boiling water for 5 minutes after cleaning, and then analyzed them with electron microscopes and spectrometers.
According to the study, they found that a single tea bag released more than 11.6 billion plastic particles, "a few more than the previous plastic load of other foods."
Most tea bags are made of natural fiber, but many tea bag brands that use natural fibers still use plastic to seal.
Some branded tea bags have been made of paper instead of plastic, and these plastic tea bags are the subjects that researchers have tested.
Microplastics are tiny fragments of plastic that the researchers define as being between 100 nanometers and 5 millimeters in size, mainly from the decomposition of plastic waste.
Researchers have found traces of microplastics in air, soil, rivers and deepest trenches around the world, and these microplastics can also be found in tap water, bottled water, seafood and beer.
For the first time in October 2018, researchers found microplastics in human fecal samples in several countries in different regions of the world.
To test the potential toxicity of the tea bag to release microplastics, the Canadian team put water fleas into contaminated water and found that microplastics affected the behavior of these fleas and caused them to develop deformities.
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), there is no evidence so far that ingesting microplastics poses a threat to humans.
However, the WHO said more research was needed to fully understand how these plastics spread to the environment and what impact it has on humans.
The researchers speculate that the reason why these tea bags release a large number of plastic particles may be that these plastic tea bags are in contact with boiling water, and even when the "edible grade" plastic is heated to more than 40 degrees Celsius, it may break down or ooze toxic substances.
