China Releases China-UN Report on Climate Change, Sustainable Development and Other Issues
Xinhua News Agency, United Nations, September 26 (Reporter Xu Xiaolei Wang Wen) On September 26, the Chinese delegation to the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly officially released the "China and the United Nations - The 74th Session of the United Nations General Assembly China Position Paper", "United Nations Climate Action Summit: China's Position and Action", "China's Progress Report on Implementing the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development (2019)", "Earth Big Data Support Sustainable Development Goals Report" and other four documents.
The China Position Paper of the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly summarizes the achievements and development of cooperation between China and the United Nations in various fields in the 70 years since the founding of New China, especially since the 18th CPC National Congress.
It is pointed out that the promotion of the construction of a community with a shared future for mankind proposed by Chinese President Xi Jinping has become the banner of diplomacy of major countries with Chinese characteristics.
Under the guidance of Xi Jinping's diplomatic thinking, China has participated in international affairs with a more positive and promising attitude, made greater contributions to world peace and development, and shouldered more responsibilities.
China has always been a builder of world peace, a contributor to global development and a defender of the international order.
The document introduces China's important contribution to the three pillars of United Nations peace, development and human rights from ten aspects.
Reaffirm that China firmly supports and practices multilateralism and supports the United Nations in playing a central role in international affairs; points out that China's development resonates with the development of the world, and the two promote each other; and emphasizes that in the face of the great changes that the world has not seen in a hundred years, a developing China will contribute more and more positive energy to the world.
The United Nations Climate Action Summit: China's Position and Action closely follow the nine areas of action of the United Nations Climate Action Summit and introduce China's policy proposition on international cooperation on climate change and China's achievements in combating climate change.
As the world's largest developing country, China regards combating climate change as an inherent requirement for its own sustainable development and its responsibility to build a community with a shared future for mankind, and will continue to overcome many difficult challenges facing its own development, firmly safeguard multilateralism, implement international commitments, and make every effort to promote the full and effective implementation of the Paris Agreement.
China's Progress Report on the Implementation of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development (2019) is China's second progress report issued after the implementation progress report was released in 2017.
The report comprehensively combs through China's measures, progress, challenges and next steps in implementing the 2030 Agenda, and demonstrates China's determination and achievements in implementing the new development concept and achieving high-quality development.
The cases of accurate poverty alleviation, innovation and leading development, ecological civilization construction, rural revitalization, and joint construction of the "Belt and Road" included in the report will provide useful reference for other countries to implement the 2030 Agenda.
The "Earth Big Data Supports Sustainable Development Goals Report" shows China's exploration and practice of using Earth Big Data to support the implementation of the 2030 Agenda and policy decision-making, reveals the application value and prospects of relevant technologies and methods for monitoring and evaluating the sustainable development goals, and provides a new perspective and new support for the international community to fill data and methodological gaps and accelerate the implementation of the 2030 Agenda.
