Electronic cigarettes in the United States have lost 12 lives and related lung damage has reached 805 cases.
According to the Central News Agency, on the 26th local time, U.S. health officials said that 12 people in the United States have died from e-cigarette-related diseases, and there are 805 cases of lung damage related to vaping.
The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported that the numbers had not been identified as specific substances that caused the disease.
However, most patients have reported the use of e-cigarette products containing tetrahydrocannabinol, which are the main compounds in cannabis that affect the state of the mind.
The surge in lung cases has been linked to the purchase of contaminated electronic smoke devices on the black market.
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said the 12 deaths occurred in 10 states from California to Florida, while the 805-related confirmed and suspected cases were reported by 46 states and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
In the past three weeks, India and Massachusetts have banned e-cigarette sales, while New York and Michigan have banned flavored e-cigarettes.
The Trump administration plans to ban all flavored e-cigarette products except tobacco flavors in October.
