The Fair Work Commission found that a Foodworks supermarket owner fired a 66-year-old woman by text message because he preferred to hire employees from Asian-American backgrounds, and the boss's practice was slammed as "disgraceful."
The commission said the way Ms. Gail Ayton, who has worked at the Wagga Wagga store for more than 20 years, was “extremely unfair” and could violate anti-discrimination laws.
Ms. Ayton told the committee that Mr. Wang had taken over the store in 2016 and that he had been "wanting to fire me" because she was not Chinese.
In this case, Deputy Chairman Peter Sams conducted a search on the Internet and found that "Mr. Wang has published some job advertisements on various Chinese employment forums in Australia in the past".
Among the job requirements listed for these positions, one said "Preferred Asian Lady" and the other said "Preferred Asian Employee".
The third post said that he "prefers to be overseas people (sic)".
Mr. Wang fired Ms. Ayton via text message in April, which he later said was due to her absence and a small cash deficit from the cash register allegedly from $5.10 to $30.
But Mr. Sams said Mr. Wang had weak reasons for dismissing Ms. Ayton and lacked evidence.
In the past three years, she has only been absent from one shift, and the "missing amount" totals a few Australian dollars.
He said Ms Ayton's dismissal "has nothing to do with her behavior or performance in fact".
"In my opinion, with the support of the evidence from the job ads issued by Mr. Wang, the real motivation for the debate to fire her is that he prefers to hire employees with Asian backgrounds," he said.
Under section 772(f) of the Fair Work Act, Mr. Wang's actions ostensibly constitute a violation of the anti-discrimination law and/or dismissal of the applicant are unlawful.
Mr Sams said it was inappropriate for Mr. Wang to consider reinstating her post, given Mr. Wang ' s "horrible" treatment of Ms. Ayton.
He should consider paying compensation to Ms. Ayton, a temporary worker with a salary of $26 an hour.
Given possible violations of anti-discrimination and labor relations legislation, Sams said he would refer his decisions and documents to the committee’s supervisor to consider whether Mr. Wang’s actions should be turned over to other agencies to investigate possible violations of state or federal law.
He said Mr. Wang had not given Ms. Ayton any chance to respond to the reasons allegedly fired from her.
"I think that the debate should take an incorrigible injustice and biased procedure to dismiss the applicant, and Mr. Wang 'waits' for this opportunity, which he believes will 'prove' that it is justified to terminate the applicant's employment," he said.
“He is wrong ... the debate should be dismissed completely disregarding any natural and fair treatment given to her, and it is shocking that he is indecent and extremely unfair perfunctory.”
Mr. Sams said that while Foodworks is a small business, “it must be frank that no decent employer will be able to lay off employees in the way that they acknowledge in this case in a way that is extremely unfair and perfunctory.”
He said, "It's shameful, and it's extremely unfair."
