China is expected to become Australia’s largest beef export market.
An animal protein analyst at Rabobank said China faced a severe pork shortage after the outbreak of African swine fever, which is expected to become Australia's largest beef export market.
After the outbreak, Chinese consumers were switching from edible pork to other animal protein, which caused authorities to destroy many herds, and in the past year, the number of pigs in China has been halved and pork prices have almost doubled.
China produces and consumes two-thirds of the world’s pork.
Chenjun Pan, a senior animal protein analyst at Rabobank China, said demand for other meats, including beef, has increased, with China, the world's largest importer of animal protein, currently importing 27% of the world's pork and 24% of the world's beef imports.
Ms Pan said that in the first half of this year, China's beef imports from Australia increased by 65%, and China surpassed the United States and Japan to become Australia's largest beef export market.
Yesterday, the Chinese government said it would release more pork from its emergency reserves before celebrating the 70th anniversary of the Chinese Communist Party’s rule.
