Study: U.S. National Healthy Eating Index Grows Slightly, but Still Challenging
According to the American Overseas Chinese Daily Network reported on September 27, recently, a new study in the United States shows that in the past 16 years, the U.S. government's healthy eating index has increased moderately, from 56 to 58.
But with a score of 100, it’s not worth celebrating.
Americans still face “significant challenges” in their diet.
Dr. Fang Fang Zhang, a nutrition researcher at Tufts University in Massachusetts and one of the authors of the study, said that Americans still consume too much food that may cause diseases such as heart disease, diabetes, and obesity, which are the most common diseases of the American people.
The study was published in the Journal of the American Medical Association on the 24th.
The study is based on findings from the U.S. government’s health survey of 44,000 adults conducted between 1999 and 2016.
The authors write that “significant dietary challenges persist despite considerable improvement.”
These challenges include allowing Americans to reduce their intake of foods that contain saturated fat, such as snacks, hot dogs, fat cows, and butter.
The study found that people's daily diet intake of these unhealthy fats increased from 11.5% to 12%, exceeding the recommended upper limit of 10%.
The biggest improvement in the American diet was a reduction in sugar intake from 16% to about 14%, but the intake was still too high.
Officials believe that the daily diet, added sugar intake should be less than 10%.
For the reasons for the reduction in sugar intake, the researchers believe that it is related to the reduction in people drinking sweet soda, but Zhang Fangfang stressed that sugar is often added to even not sweet foods, such as yogurt and ketchup.
U.S. adults had a small increase in the intake of fruit, nuts, oats, and other whole grains.
However, data from 2016 show that these foods still account for less than 5% of their daily diet.
Although people's intake of salt is slightly reduced, and the reduction in drinking juices leads to low-quality carbohydrate intake, Zhang Fangfang said that they still account for as much as 42% of daily calories, many of which come from refined white bread and other refined grains.
The study is based on a two-year-old survey of personal health that causes adults to recall what they have eaten in the past 24 hours.
These health surveys have asked this question twice every few days since 2003.
The government's Dietary Guidelines for U.S. residents recommend a "healthy eating pattern" to reduce the likelihood of chronic disease.
The guidelines state that people should consume more nutrient-dense foods such as vegetables, fruits, whole grains, low-fat dairy products, and seafood, lean meat, poultry, eggs, and seed foods that can provide protein.
The number of Americans living with diabetes has nearly doubled to more than 7 percent during the survey period, and obesity rates have increased over many years - about 70 percent of U.S. adults are overweight or obese today.
In addition, heart disease remains the leading cause of death among Americans.
