According to the Central News Agency, the United Nations International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) said on the 26th that Iran's use of advanced centrifuges to make enriched uranium has once again violated the Iranian nuclear agreement.
According to reports, Iran is gradually violating the restrictions of the Iranian nuclear agreement in response to US President Trump's withdrawal from the Iranian nuclear agreement in May 2018, the restoration and strengthening of sanctions against Iran.
Iran suspended two other commitments in July to keep its stockpile of enriched uranium below 300 kilograms and enrich uranium to no more than 3.67% purity.
Under the nuclear deal, Iran could only set up about 5,000 first-generation IR-1 centrifuges in Natanz to accumulate uranium enrichment, and only allowed Iran to use a small number of more advanced models for research, but did not produce enriched uranium.
If Iran succeeds in developing more advanced centrifuges, it will be able to produce enriched uranium several times faster, possibly for the production of nuclear bombs.
According to the report, the International Atomic Energy Agency reported: "On September 25, the agency has confirmed that Iran's advanced centrifuges with models 2 and 3 ... are accumulating or are ready to accumulate enriched uranium."
